  "opinion": "As a 75-year-old retired woman living in Washington DC, I've seen a lot change over the years, and dealing with fake content on social media is something that weighs on my mind, especially given my tendency toward depression and high neuroticism. I use social media a few times a week, mostly to stay connected with family and friends, play video games, and share photos from my travels and hiking trips. From my perspective, managing fake content starts with a personal commitment to truth and kindness, rooted in my Christian beliefs. I believe in approaching this issue with a high level of agreeableness, as I value harmony and trust, but I've learned to be cautious. When I come across something suspicious, like a sensational news story or a too-good-to-be-true offer, I don't just share it impulsively. Instead, I take a moment to check reliable sources, often recalling lessons from my vocational diploma and my parent's mixed educational backgrounds—my father had no formal education, but my mother had a master's degree, which taught me to appreciate diverse perspectives but also seek verified information. I think it's important to talk about fake content openly with others, especially younger folks I meet through my hobbies, to foster a culture of skepticism without cynicism. Given my moderate conscientiousness, I'm not always meticulous, but I make an effort to report false posts when I can, and I limit my time online to avoid the stress that fuels my depression. Ultimately, I see managing fake content as a shared responsibility: we all need to slow down, think critically, and support each other in navigating this digital world, much like we do on a hiking trail where we watch out for each other's safety.",
